		<div class="entry">
			<span itemprop="articleBody"><p><div id="attachment_11387" style="width: 670px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img src="http://www.wired.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/crowdsurf_660.jpg" alt="Image: Photos by Mavis/Flickr" width="660" height="330" class="size-full wp-image-11387"><p class="wp-caption-text"><em>Image: Photos by Mavis/Flickr</em></p></div>
</p><p>The United States has a government of the people, by the people, and for the people, and the talents, energy, and creativity of the American public are our Nation&rsquo;s greatest assets. &nbsp;</p>
<p>In the Internet age, we are in a better position than ever before to harness the problem-solving prowess of our fellow citizens through digital tools and crowdsourcing. From reCAPTCHA, which allows Internet users to digitize archived copies of <em>The New York Times</em>, to Wikipedia&rsquo;s <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Size_of_Wikipedia" target="_blank">more than 32 million pages</a>&nbsp;that are written and updated by interested citizens, to apps that crowdsource real-time traffic information and restaurant recommendations from members of the public &mdash; we&rsquo;ve seen firsthand that unlocking the wisdom of the crowds can lead to better solutions.</p>
<p>One place you might not expect has long used crowdsourcing as a tool to tap into the talents and abilities of our citizens &mdash; the Federal Government. For example, the origin of today&rsquo;s National Weather Service actually tracks back to <a href="http://siarchives.si.edu/history/jhp/joseph03.htm" target="_blank">a crowdsourcing project</a>&nbsp;led by the Smithsonian Institution more than 150 years ago, enlisting volunteers from across the country to submit weather observations to Washington via telegraph.</p>
<p>While we have come a long way from the days of citizens sharing information via telegraph, the premise still rings true: Engaging American citizens as strategic partners in solving, creating, and innovating pays off.&nbsp;</p>
<p>That&rsquo;s why right now, we are working to boost crowdsourcing efforts across government through our&nbsp;<a href="http://www.whitehouse.gov/innovationfellows" target="_blank">Presidential Innovation Fellows Program</a>&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;an initiative that pairs talented, diverse individuals from outside government with top Federal innovators to implement game-changing projects that make the Federal Government&nbsp;&nbsp;work better for the American people.</p>
<p>Our recent track record might surprise you: Across government, agencies are implementing hundreds of crowdsourcing approaches, <a href="http://www.whitehouse.gov/champions/citizen-scientists" target="_blank">citizen science programs</a>, and other efforts to harness American ingenuity. Last year alone, Federal agencies ran over 85 prize competitions, from small-dollar prizes to winnings of $100,000 or more. And the government pays only for results. So far, these collaborations have resulted in creative solutions including new designs for <a href="http://www.nasa.gov/offices/oct/early_stage_innovation/centennial_challenges/astronaut_glove/index.html" target="_blank">improved astronaut space suit gloves</a>, <a href="http://disability.challengepost.com/" target="_blank">innovative tools for job seekers</a>, and <a href="http://robocall.challengepost.com/" target="_blank">new ways to block illegal robocalls</a>.</p>
<p>Crowdsourcing allows the government to reach beyond the &ldquo;usual suspects&rdquo; to expand and diversify the talent pool tackling a problem. For example, a recent <a href="http://www.topcoder.com/iss/longeron" target="_blank">Challenge led by NASA</a>&nbsp;spurred over 2,000 new proposals for software algorithms to make solar panels on the International Space Station more efficient. Top entries provided NASA a range of promising new ideas and options for positioning the panels to maximize energy collected from the sun and reduce shadows the station casts upon itself at various points during its orbits of Earth.</p>
<p>We also saw first-hand the value of <a href="http://mashable.com/2013/05/05/brian-forde-sandy-technology/" target="_blank">crowdsourcing information during Hurricane Sandy</a>&nbsp;when tech companies, voluntary organizations, federal agencies, and the White House worked together to build tools to help citizens, first responders, and local, state and Federal officials determine critical information such as which gas stations were open, had fuel, and had power from a backup generator. Together we worked with tech companies like Waze, a crowdsourced mapping tool, to release user feedback about gas stations, and the All Hazards Consortium and Hughes Network Systems to provide point-of-sale information to determine which gas stations appeared open and operational. We encouraged students at Franklin High School in New Jersey monitoring thousands of local tweets to create a database of information on gas stations. We encouraged those students to open up the database so other platforms could benefit from this real-time information.</p>
<p>Together, we collaborated with Google, which compiled this information and displayed it in its popular Google Crisis Map. This map, along with others, helped the federal government better understand the needs of the people impacted by the hurricane, while also providing useful information directly to survivors and local responders.</p>
<p>These are just a few examples of government-driven crowdsourcing competitions and collaborations that have brought the best ideas and talent together to solve mission-centric problems. And the <a href="http://www.nasa.gov/pdf/572344main_InnoCentive_NASA_PublicReport_2011-0422.pdf" target="_blank">evidence</a>&nbsp;suggests that most citizen solvers participating in these efforts have never before worked with the government.</p>
<p><a href="http://www.whitehouse.gov/blog/2014/03/06/presidential-innovation-fellows-round-3-serve-create-innovate" target="_blank">Now we are looking</a>&nbsp;for incredibly talented individuals from diverse backgrounds to help us expand these efforts &mdash; original thinkers, gifted designers, tech-savvy strategists, inventors, entrepreneurs, and developers and engineers &mdash; to offer up their skills and expertise <a href="http://www.whitehouse.gov/sites/default/files/microsites/ostp/fact_sheet_-_pif_highlights_mar_-_2014.pdf" target="_blank">to help lead crowdsourcing projects</a>&nbsp;to <a href="http://www.whitehouse.gov/sites/default/files/microsites/ostp/fact_sheet_-_pif_highlights_mar_-_2014.pdf" target="_blank">create huge value for the public</a>.</p>
<p><a href="http://www.whitehouse.gov/innovationfellows/projects" target="_blank">Opportunities</a>&nbsp;for Presidential Innovation Fellows include creating new crowdsourcing tools to empower survivors and first responders during natural disasters, significantly improving the quality of our patent system, and even addressing asteroid threats to human populations.</p>
<p>If you are interested in lending your talents and expertise to help transform how government works for the people it serves, then you should consider <a href="http://www.whitehouse.gov/blog/2014/03/06/presidential-innovation-fellows-round-3-serve-create-innovate" target="_blank">joining the ranks</a>&nbsp;of the Presidential Innovation Fellows&nbsp;.</p>
<p>We may not be able to offer free lunches, but we can offer the unique opportunity to work on truly awesome projects with the potential to make a positive impact &mdash; with a user base of more than 300 million Americans. That&rsquo;s innovation making a difference.</p>
<p><strong><em>Join a startup whose founders are already in your history books! <span style="text-decoration: underline;">The White House is <a href="http://pif.gsa.gov" target="_blank">accepting applications</a>&nbsp;until Monday April 7th for the next round of the Presidential Innovation Fellows (PIF) program.</span></em></strong></p>
<p><em>Cristin Dorgelo is the Assistant Director for Grand Challenges. Brian Forde, who co-authored this post, is the Senior Advisor to the U.S. Chief Technology Officer. Both serve the White House Office of Science and Technology Policy.</em></p>
